THE CATCHES OF FISH IN THE GILLNETS WAS DOWN FROM THE 1985 CATCH. CISCO WERE DOWN 35%, NORTHERN PIKE 28%, WHITE SUCKER 42%, ROCK BASS 37%, BLACK CRAPPIE 67% YELLOW PERCH 47% SAUGER 77% AND WALL- EYE WERE DOWN 47% FROM THE 1985 CATCH. YOY WALLEYE WERE DOWN 78%, YOY YELLOW PERCH 57% AND YOY WHITE SUCKERS WERE DOWN 43% FROM THE 1985 SEINING YOY BLACK CRAPPIES WERE UP 3.2 TIMES FROM THE 1985 SEINE CATCHES.

WALLEYE CPUE DECREASED FROM 9.35 FISH/NET IN 1987 TO 6.15 FISH/NET IN 1988. THE MEAN SIZE OF WALLEYE INCREASED 0.2 LBS. FROM 1987. MUCH OF THE CHANGES IN THE WALLEYE POPULATION CAN BE ATTRIBUTED TO THE STRONG 1984 YEAR CLASS AGING IN THE FISHERY. WALL- EYE RECRUITMENT TO GILLNETS WAS EVIDENT FOR ALL RECENT YEARS; HOWEVER, THE 1985 YEAR CLASS APPEARS TO BE SMALLER THAN THE 1987 ASSESSMENT WOULD HAVE INDICATED. WALLEYE GROWTH RATES WERE HIGHER THAN 1987. NORTHERN PIKE CPUE AND SIZE DISTRIBUTION WERE SIMILAR TO LAST YEAR. YELLOW PERCH AND SAUGER INDEX OF ABUNDANCE WAS UP FROM 1987.

Namakan Lake is part of the Namakan Resevoir that includes Kabetogama, Sand point, Crane, and Little Vermilion lakes. Gill netting is conducted annually in Namakan Lake to assess fish populations.The walleye catch was 4.9/gill net, which was the lowest catch in the last 11 years. However, it was still within the normal range for this type of lake. The low catch rate may have been a result of three consecutive weak year classes. However, the 1994 year class appeared to be very strong, and should provide good angling opportunities for the next few years. The average size of walleye was 13.2", and the largest walleye observed was 21.9".Sauger catch rate was also low for Namakan Lake at 1.8/gill net. Age class distribution was similar to that for walleye, and probably contributed to the low catch rate. Sauger averaged 11.1". Growth rates for both walleye and sauger in Namakan Lake were lower than the state averages for those species.Northern pike catch rate was average for this lake type at 1.6 per gill net. The pike tended to be fairly large. The average length was 25.3", and the average weight was 4.2 lbs. Approximately 13% of the pike were longer than 34".Forage species included yellow perch, tullibee, and white sucker. Catch rates for these three species were within the normal ranges. Other species sampled in low numbers included lake sturgeon, smallmouth bass, black crappie, rock bass, black bullhead, and burbot, and redhorse.

Namakan Lake is located on the border between Minnesota and the Province of Ontario and is part of the Namakan Reservoir, which also consists of Crane, Kabetogama, Little Vermilion, and Sand Point lakes. There is no road access to several of the lakes. Thus, anglers gain access by traveling by boat from road access points located on Crane or Kabetogama lakes.

Black crappie abundance was below the expected range for this lake type; which is different from recent years, when crappie abundance exceeded expectation. Black crappie fishing has become more popular recently on Namakan Lake, especially in winter. Most anglers have been attracted by the large crappies present in Namakan Lake. The largest crappie captured during the 2010 fisheries investigation was 9.7 inches.

Northern pike abundance was within the expected range for this lake type. Abundance has increased 35 percent since 2000; the year which the rule-curve used to regulate water levels was changed to enhance northern pike spawning habitat. Size remains impressive and anglers have a good chance to catch very large northern pike. Our sample in 2010 found fish up to 40.1 inches.

Sauger are present but generally are rare and sizes are small. The average size sampled in 2010 was 10.1 inches and the average weight was 0.27 pounds.

Smallmouth bass is another choice for anglers visiting Namakan Lake. Abundance in 2010 was within the expected range for this lake type. The average size in our sample was 12.4 inches, a fun size for anglers. Typically, anglers also catch some very large fish while targeting smallmouth bass on Namakan Lake. Some true trophy-sized fish are out there.

Walleye abundance was within the expected range for this lake type. Size in the sample ranged from 6.6-23.3 inches. Walleye ranged from 0-16 years old and age-4 fish represented 37 percent of the sample. The walleye born in 2006 are the third strongest year-class in the past 25 years. These fish will continue to grow larger and provide opportunities for great fishing in the future.

Yellow perch abundance was near the top of the expected range for this lake type. However, sizes in this lake type are generally small. Although yellow perch are unlikely to interest most angers, they are important forage for predators.

Namakan Lake is a 25,130 acre, class 2 lake, located along the border between Minnesota and the Province of Ontario. The Minnesota portion (12,314 acres) is located in Voyageurs National Park. Namakan Lake is part of the Namakan Reservoir, which also includes Crane, Kabetogama, Little Vermilion, and Sand Point lakes. There is no road access on the Minnesota portion of Namakan Lake. Thus, anglers gain access by traveling by boat from road access points located on Crane or Kabetogama lakes. Black bullheads, black crappies, cisco, golden shiners, lake sturgeon, lake whitefish, northern pike, rock bass, saugers, smallmouth bass, walleyes, white suckers, and yellow perch were captured in gill nets in 2000. Northern pike gill net abundance was slightly above average compared to similar lakes (class 2). Six year-classes were present and age ranged from 1-6 years. Total length ranged from 20.9-39.0 inches, and growth was much higher than the statewide and area averages. Average weight was also higher than similar lakes. Walleye gill net abundance was near the average for this lake type. However, overall walleye abundance was down 56% from the 1999 population assessment and fish from the 1996 year-class were down 78%. In 1999, 156 walleyes from the 1996 year-class were captured; the number dropped to 35 in 2000. The change in abundance was mostly due to the large 1996 year-class of fish moving into the unprotected zone of the slot limit on Namamkan Lake and the subsequent angling harvest prior to our population assessment. In 2000, nine walleye year-classes were present and age ranged from 1-11 years. Strong year-classes were produced in 1994, 1996, and 1998. Total length ranged from 6.8-23.3 inches and the mean was 13.7. Growth was less than the area and statewide averages. Mean weight of walleyes was similar to other class 2 lakes. Yellow perch gill net abundance was above average for class 2 lakes. Six year-classes were present and age ranged from 2-7 years. Age-3 fish composed 50% of the sample. Total length ranged from 5.1-9.6 inches and the mean was 7.2. Growth was the same as lakes in this area, but below the statewide average.

Walleye gill-net abundance was 9.90 fish/set, which was above last year's level of 6.00 fish/set and the median of 6.32 fish/set for lake class 2. Thirteen year-classes were present and age ranged from 0-13 years. The 1998 year-class represented 41% of the sample. Total length ranged from 4.4-22.8 inches and the mean was 13.7. Growth was slower than the area and statewide averages. Mean weight of walleyes was the same as the median for class 2 lakes. Yellow perch gill-net abundance was 3.50 fish/set, which was below the median of 4.53 fish/set for class 2 lakes. Five year-classes were present and age ranged from 2-6 years. Age-4 fish were the most common and represented 43% of the sample. Total length ranged from 5.5-10.1 inches and the mean was 7.3. Growth was the same as the area average, but below the statewide average.

Black crappies, cisco, lake sturgeon, lake whitefish, northern pike, rock bass, saugers, silver redhorse, smallmouth bass, walleyes, white suckers, and yellow perch were captured in during the assessment in 2004. Black crappie gill-net abundance was 0.20 fish/set, which was the lowest level recorded since 1996. Total length (TL) ranged from 4.1-8.5 inches and the mean was 5.7. The mean weight was below what is found in most class 2 lakes. Northern pike gill-net abundance (1.50 fish/set) was slightly below the median for class 2 lakes (1.62 fish/set). Six year-classes were present and age ranged from 2-9 years. Maximum size was exceptional; total length ranged from 17.9-42.3 inches and the mean was 25.7. Growth was also outstanding; the mean TL at age-4 of 25.4 inches was much higher than the statewide mean of 21.1 inches and the area mean of 23.7 inches. The mean weight was above the third quartile for class 2 lakes. Walleye gill-net abundance was 8.85 fish/set, which was above the lake class median of 6.32. Thirteen year-classes were present and age ranged from 1-17 years. Age-3 fish represented 30% of the sample. Total length ranged from 7.0-27.5 inches and the mean was 14.8. Walleye growth was slow in Namakan; mean TL at age-4 was 11.3 inches, well below the area (14.4) and statewide (15.1) averages. Mean weight of walleyes was greater than the third quartile for class 2 lakes. Yellow perch gill-net abundance was 3.65 fish/set, which was below the median for class 2 lakes. Six year-classes were present and age ranged from 2-7 years. Age-3 fish represented 60% of the sample. Total length ranged from 5.2-10.8 inches and the mean was 6.6. Mean TL at age-4 was 6.6 inches, which was equal to the area average, but below the statewide average of 7.2 inches.

Namakan Lake is located approximately thirty miles east-southeast of International Falls, Minnesota on the international border between Minnesota and Ontario, Canada. Namakan is part of the Namakan Reservoir, which also consists of Kabetogama, Sand Point, Crane, and Little Vermilion lakes. The reservoir system typically consists of dark stained waters with low densities of vegetation and an abundance of rock. The Minnesota portion of Namakan lies within Voyageurs National Park, and does not have a road access. Anglers can access Namakan by boat from road access points located on Crane or Kabetogama lakes, or through a network of snowmobile trails in winter. Namakan has high quality populations of several species of gamefish, and is typically surveyed annually to monitor those fish populations.

Black Crappie are not typically caught in great numbers in the sampling gear used to survey Namakan each year. Crappie catch rates in 2018 were equal to what would be expected in lakes similar to Namakan, and the average size was slightly larger than what would be expected. Black Crappie averaged 8.5 inches and some over 11 inches were in the sample.

Cisco are an important forage species for larger predator fish. Catch rates in 2018 were up from the 2017 survey, but still slightly less than the average catch rate for Namakan. Cisco ranged from about 7 to 18 inches.

Northern Pike catch rates were similar to the historic average for Namakan. There is always potential to catch a trophy fish here. Pike caught during the 2018 survey ranged from 15 to 41 inches, and averaged 4.25 pounds. Ages from Northern Pike ranged from 1 to 10 years old.

Sauger catch rates were close to the long term average for Namakan. Sauger do not typically reach large sizes in Namakan, but can provide some bonus fillets for anglers targeting fish for harvest. The average Sauger sampled in 2018 was 10 inches.

Smallmouth Bass catch rates were within the expected range for Namakan. Average size was greater than what would be expected for similar lakes. Smallmouth ranged from approximately 9 to 17 inches and averaged 13 to 14 inches.

Walleye catch rates were up from 2017, and greater than the historic mean for Namakan. Anglers targeting harvestable size Walleye have ample opportunities to do so as the average size was just under 14 inches. Fairly consistent year class production also means that a wide range of sizes are available to anglers, including trophy sized fish. The 2011 year class remains the strongest in recent history.

Yellow Perch catch rates were also near the historic mean for Namakan, which is slightly more than average for similar lakes. The average size of Yellow Perch in Namakan is also greater than would be expected for similar lakes. The average length in 2018 was over 8 inches and fish over 12 inches were in the sample. Perch up to 11 years old were aged, but the 2 to 6 year olds made up over 90% of the catch.

Other fish caught during the 2018 survey included Burbot, Lake Sturgeon, Lake Whitefish, Redhorse, Rock Bass, and White Sucker.

Namakan Lake is a 25,130 acre, softwater lake, located along the border between Minnesota and the Province of Ontario. The lake has a rocky irregular shoreline and tannin stained water typical of Canadian Shield lakes. The Minnesota portion (12,322 acres) is located within the boundaries of Voyageurs National Park. Namakan Lake is part of the Namakan Reservoir, which also includes Crane, Kabetogama, Little Vermilion and Sand Point lakes. There is no road access on the Minnesota side of the lake. Thus, most anglers gain access by traveling via boat or snowmobile from road access points located on Crane or Kabetogama Lakes. A mechanical portage does exist at Kettle Falls located where Namakan flows into the east end of Rainy Lake.Twelve species were present in the 2005 Fall Assessment gill netting on Namakan Lake. Cisco was the most common species in the catch making up 28% of the total by number. Yellow perch, walleye and northern pike were also common. Northern pike had the highest total weight in the catch.Walleye abundance in 2005 (5.70/net) was the lowest recorded since 1997 on Namakan Lake. In spite of the low abundance recorded this year, gill-net abundance has shown an increasing trend since sampling was standardized in 1983 and, in recent years, has become more stable. The abundance of walleye over 17 inches in length also appears to be increasing. Lengths of walleye averaged 14.6 inches with the largest individual measuring 26.7 inches. Walleye growth for Namakan Lake was slower than the Area and Statewide averages.Fourteen year-classes were present in the walleye catch and ages ranged from 0-22 years. Most walleye were from the 2001 year-class (27% of captured walleye) and the 1999 year-class (18% of captured walleye). Fewer age-5 (2000 year-class) and age-3 (2002 year-class) walleye were captured than is normal for these age-groups. More year-classes are reaching maturity than ever before. Northern pike abundance (2.40/net) exceeded the median of 1.62/net for lakes of this classification. The 2005 northern pike gill-net catch also was the third highest of all previous fisheries investigations on Namakan Lake. High abundance in 2005 was consistent with the positive trend in pike abundance noted since the early 1990's. Lengths of captured northern pike ranged from 16.4 to 38.6 inches with an average of 25.2 inches. Four pike over 36 inches in length were reported in the catch. The average weight for captured northern pike (4.26 pounds) exceeded the average for this lake class (3.52 pounds). Growth of Namakan Lake northern pike was considerably faster than the Area median. The 2001 year-class appears to be strong in number.Although gill-net catches of smallmouth bass on Namakan Lake tend to be variable, they do indicate that bass abundance has increased since the early 1960's. The 2005 gill-net catch (0.50/net) was the eighth highest on record for Namakan Lake and exceeded the median for this lake class. The nine bass caught during this investigation averaged 12.3 in length. Growth of Namakan Lake smallmouth bass exceeded the Area median. Other species present in the gill-net catch included black crappie, burbot, lake whitefish, rock bass, sauger, silver lamprey, cisco and white sucker.

This is consistent with previous investigations on Namakan Lake. Although walleye up to 27" long were sampled in gillnets, the average length was 13.2", and average weight was 1.0 pounds. These averages are probably influenced by relatively slow growth rates of walleye in Namakan Lake, and a lack of walleye ages 5 and older. Northern pike abundance as sampled by test nets is lower than what is typically observed on similar lakes, which indicates a low density northern pike population. However, the northern pike in Namakan Lake are fast growing and large, with an average length of 27.3" and an average weight of 5.8 pounds. Sauger gillnet catch rates are less than what is normally observed in similar lakes in the International Falls area. This is a departure from recent investigations, and suggests a decline in sauger abundance has occurred. The average length of sauger sampled in gillnets was 9.7", and average weight was 0.2 pounds.

Introduction
This investigation was designed to document the population characteristics of Lake Whitefish (Coregonus clupeaformis) found in Namakan and Sand Point Lakes, Minnesota. Changes in water level management first enacted by the International Joint Commission (IJC) in 2000 were expected to be beneficial to Lake Whitefish in the Namakan Reservoir. Lake Whitefish spawn in shallow water during October and November with eggs hatching early in the following spring. Whitefish eggs, therefore, are susceptible to desiccation during winters with significant water level drawdown.

This investigation used the Fish Community Index Netting (FCIN) protocol developed by the Province of Ontario (LNFAU 2001) to collect long-term population characteristics of Lake Whitefish in Namakan and Sand Point Lakes. FCIN is carried out on a two out of four year rotation. The 2021 sampling season represents the first of two surveys in the current four year rotation on the Namakan Reservoir.
Methods

Nine FCIN nets were set from August 15th through August 18rd, 2021 on Namakan Lake. Three additional sets were made on Sand Point Lake on August 18th and lifted on August 19th. Sets were approximately 24-hours in duration. Gill nets used were eight feet tall and consisted of nine 50-foot panels of various mesh gill net (1.0, 2.25, 0.75, 1.5, 2.5, 1.75, 0.5, 2.0, and 1.25 inch bar measure). Net locations were selected to sample two depth strata (50'-90' and greater than 90'). Six nets were set in the shallow-water stratum and three were set in the deep-water stratum of Namakan Lake, and two were set in the shallow-water stratum and one in the deep-water stratum of Sand Point Lake (Figure 1). Net location and orientation was chosen randomly within strata across the entire lake. However, nets could not be within 330 feet of shore or exposed shoals.

All fish captured in each net were separated by species and capture mesh. Total length, weight, sex, and state of maturity were recorded for all Lake Whitefish captured. Otoliths were collected from Lake Whitefish for aging.

Five metrics were incorporated to track long-term trends in the Lake Whitefish population (LNFAU 2001).
1) Mean age of first maturity
2) Mean age of FCIN catch
3) Relative abundance (Catch per unit effort (CPUE))
4) Recruitment/ juvenile abundance (CPUE of age 3, 4 and 5)
5) Spatial distribution of FCIN catch

Results and Discussion

Seven species totaling 457 individual fish were caught in the 2021 summer FCIN assessment (Table 1). Cisco species were the most common fish by number and weight, making up 72.4 percent of the total catch by number and 31.9 percent of the catch by weight. Walleyes and Lake Whitefish made up the next largest portion of the total weight at 22.3 and 18.0 percent of the catch, respectively. Twenty-eight Lake Whitefish were sampled for a catch rate of 2.3 per lift. A total of 331 Cisco (27.6 per net), 40 Burbot (3.3 per net), 35 Walleyes (2.9 per net), 12 Sauger (1.0 per net), nine White Suckers (0.8 per net), and two Northern Pike (0.3 per net) were caught during the 2021 FCIN survey.

Lake Whitefish ranged in length from 9.8 to 21.7 inches, with a mean of 16.3 (Table 2). The mean weight was 1.7 pounds. Twelve age-classes were represented in the 2021 catch with the age 7 year-class composing 25.0 percent of the total catch while the age 2 and age 5 year-classes each made up an additional 14.3 percent of the total catch (Table 3).

Five metrics for evaluating the Lake Whitefish population were calculated. The age of 50% maturity (females) was 10.6 years. The mean age of Lake Whitefish in the FCIN catch was 6.8 years. Recruitment criteria showed that the juvenile abundance (CPUE of age 3, 4, 5) of Lake Whitefish was 0.5 per net, although there were five additional juvenile fish caught that were less than age 3 (4 age-2 and 1 age-1). Lake Whitefish were sampled at 10 of 12 stations (Figure 2).

FCIN sampling from recent years suggest the Lake Whitefish population is relatively stable. Sampling was carried out in a two of four year rotation resulting in 10 years of sampling between 2004 and 2021. Lake Whitefish catch rates have fluctuated between 1.33 per net and 4.60 per net and averaged 3.0 per net. There is no longer a commercial fishery for Lake Whitefish on the Minnesota side of the Namakan Reservoir and recreational harvest is likely low. There were several age classes of Lake Whitefish present in the 2021 catch with individuals up to 16 years old along with several juvenile fish. Consistent catch rates of juvenile Lake Whitefish suggest good reproduction and recruitment. Monitoring of the Lake Whitefish population for signs of stress should continue.

Seven year-classes were present and age ranged from 1-7 years. Total length ranged from 16.1-38.8 inches and the growth rate was much higher than the statewide and area averages. The average weight was also above the average observed in similar lakes. Walleye gill-net abundance was 6.60 fish/set, which was below the average since 1983 of 7.57. Walleye abundance has decreased since 2001, mostly due record numbers of fish in several year-classes moving into the unprotected zone of the slot limit and the subsequent angling harvest. In 2003, eleven walleye year-classes were present and age ranged from 1-11 years. The 2001 year-class was abundant and represented 37% of the sample. These fish should keep anglers busy in the summer of 2004, as they will be near the lower end of the harvest slot. Yellow perch gill-net abundance was 1.45 fish/set, which was second lowest level ever recorded for Namakan Lake. Five year-classes were present and age ranged from 2-7 years. Age-4 fish represented 38% of the sample. Total length ranged from 5.5-9.4 inches and the average was 7.5. Growth was slightly above the area average, but below the statewide average.

While abundance has improved, variability in catches has decreased indicating more stability in population numbers. The abundance of walleye over 17 inches in length also has increased. Namakan Lake is located on the border between Minnesota and the Province of Ontario and is part of the Namakan Reservoir, which also consists of Crane, Kabetogama, Little Vermilion, and Sand Point lakes. There is no road access to several of the lakes. Thus, anglers gain access by traveling by boat from road access points located on Crane or Kabetogama lakes.

Black Crappie abundance was within the expected range for this lake type. Black Crappie fishing has become more popular recently on Namakan Lake, especially in winter. Most anglers have been attracted by the large Crappies present in Namakan Lake. The largest Crappie captured during the 2016 fisheries investigation was 10.8 inches.

Northern Pike abundance was the second highest level ever recorded on Namakan Lake above the expected range for this lake type. The rule-curve used to regulate water levels was changed in 2000 to enhance Northern Pike spawning habitat. Long-term trends suggest that the change in water levels has increased Northern Pike abundance. Size remains impressive and anglers have a good chance to catch very large Northern Pike. The sample in 2016 included fish up to 44.4 inches.

Sauger are present but generally not abundant and sizes are small. The average size sampled in 2016 was 10.0 inches and the average weight was 0.27 pounds.

Smallmouth Bass is another choice for anglers visiting Namakan Lake. Abundance in 2016 was well above the expected range for this lake type. The average size in our sample was 13.0 inches, a fun size for anglers. Typically, anglers also catch some very large fish while targeting Smallmouth Bass on Namakan Lake.

Walleye abundance was within the expected range for this lake type. Long-term trends indicate at least a 10 percent increase in Walleye abundance since a size regulation was implemented in 1998. The regulation has also improved the size structure; older, larger fish are now more abundant. In 2016, 15 year-classes were present and age ranged from 1-20 years. The 2006 year-class was the strongest in over 25 years and remains prominent. Recent year-classes look promising as well, especially the 2011 and 2012 year-classes which represented 47 percent of the sample. Size in the 2016 sample ranged from 6.9-26.1 inches and average weight was 0.90 pounds.

Yellow Perch abundance was within the expected range for this lake type. Currently, sizes exist that are attractive to anglers. The size range was from 5.6-11.0 inches and the average was 7.6.
